Welcome to the Anomaly Markup Web Service!
This service is designed for working with objects received from an individual machine learning model located in the Fink anomaly_detection module.
In this guide, we will briefly explain the overall structure of this web service and how to use it.

Purpose of the Service

The main purpose of the service is to provide each expert with their personal workspace where they can work with a stream of notifications coming from their personal model.

Each night, the user's personal account receives the top-10 objects by Anomaly score from the Anomaly detection module. These objects can be viewed either through the web service interface or via a Telegram bot (more on using the Telegram bot will be later).
Initially, a model trained on a basic dataset is created for the user. By accumulating markup, the user can request automatic retraining of the model on them via the Model Dashboard of the web service, resulting in more relevant incoming objects for the user in the future.

Terms that will be used further:

  • Expert - a service user;
  • Reaction - markup of an object by the expert. Can be "Anomaly" or "Not anomaly";
  • Notification - information about an object received from Fink. Includes cutout, light curve, object ID in the Fink, ID in the SNAD (if available), GAL coordinates, EQU coordinates, UTC observation time, real bogus and anomaly score.

Authorization

The first thing a user encounters when entering the site is the login form:

To work with an individual model, a user needs their own account, which will be associated with this model. If you do not have an account yet, you can create one through the registration form.

Anomalies

On the "Anomalies" tab, there is a list of the user's current reactions:

The list updates every time the page is loaded. Next to each reaction in the table, there are two buttons:

  • Delete - remove the reaction from the account. After this, it will not be used in model retraining;
  • Change - change the tag of the reaction to the opposite.

Notifications

On the "Notifications" tab, all unprocessed notifications received at the moment are presented. The list is sorted from the newest notification to the oldest:

Each notification has four buttons:

  • Not anomaly - mark the notification as "Not anomaly";
  • Just remove - simply delete the notification without creating any annotation;
  • TNS Submit - pre-fill the TNS Report form based on the data from this notification;
  • Anomaly - mark the notification as "Anomaly".

Telegram Bot

If it is convenient for the expert to work from the Telegram messenger, they can log in to the Telegram bot linked to the web service. To do this, the expert must perform the following steps:

  1. Go to the Telegram bot https://t.me/ZTF_anomaly_alert_bot;
  2. Send the /connect command;
  3. After the bot requests, enter the username and password for your account on the web service.
    After this, all notifications will be duplicated in the Telegram bot in the following format:

    Annotations are made by clicking the corresponding buttons at the bottom of the notification.

Model Dashboard

On the "Settings" tab, two buttons are displayed:

  • Last Update Time - the time when the expert's individual model was last trained (and the number of reactions used in this training);
  • Last Deployment Time - the time when the expert's model was last updated in production.
      Pressing the "Request Model Update" button initiates the process of training the model on the current set of reactions. The process takes about 10 minutes, after which the Last Update Time should change.

    Presumed Scheme of Service Use

    1. The expert registers an account;
    2. After the first login, the expert goes to the "Settings" tab and presses the "Request Model Update" button, after which the initial model training begins for them;
    3. After the first model training and its deployment in production, notifications begin to arrive for the expert;
    4. The expert annotates the notifications;
    5. As reactions accumulate, the model is trained on them, and the notifications become increasingly relevant for the expert.
